{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472522"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:59:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:59:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1527"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582934"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:01:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:01:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1527"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1527"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.08,0.02,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104202"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1527"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86537"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"928"},{"type":"tags","id":"2187"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5438"},{"type":"tags","id":"5445"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5671"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35529"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44851"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104202"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman brings her 12-month-old son to the General Practice clinic for his scheduled measles, mumps and rubella vaccination. She says she is worried because a friend told her the vaccine might cause autism. The child has no significant medical history. He is crawling, babbling, trying to feed himself, but not yet pulling up to stand. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well and his vital signs are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the best initial approach to the parent\u0027s concern regarding autism and the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassure the patient that there is no association","Provide a printout of the product information","Refer to an immunology specialist","Provide the parents with a link to government health websites","Suggest delaying vaccination until the parent feels comfortable"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen addressing vaccine hesitancy, it is important to respond directly to the specific concerns raised by parents. In this case, the parent is worried about a purported link between the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine and autism. \u003Cstrong\u003EReassure the patient that there is no association \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most appropriate approach. This allows the clinician to clearly communicate that extensive research has consistently shown no link between the vaccine and autism, while acknowledging the parent\u0027s concern. However, directly addressing the parent\u0027s concerns should not be done without then going on to empathise with the parent\u0027s worries and explore their concerns in further detail.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide a printout of the product information\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate approach. While product information can be helpful as an additional resource, it can use technical language and may be difficult to understand, particularly for those with low health literacy. It may also not directly address the parent\u0027s concerns regarding autism and the measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) vaccine, nor does it replace the value of a direct conversation with the family\u0027s general practitioner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer to an immunology specialist\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary for addressing this common concern. General practitioners should be equipped to discuss routine vaccination concerns, including the well-established evidence regarding autism and the MMR vaccine. Referral may delay vaccination and suggest the concern is more complex than it actually is.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide the parents with a link to government health websites\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful as an additional resource, but should not replace direct communication with a general practitioner. Parents often value and trust information provided directly by their doctor more than what they read online, and the immediate concern should be addressed during the consultation. This may be an option to provide for the parents to read at home after discussions occur in the clinic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuggest delaying vaccination until the parent feels comfortable\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as it leaves the child vulnerable to preventable diseases without addressing the underlying concern. Delaying vaccination without medical indication increases the risk to the child and community, and may reinforce unfounded concerns. The parents would also be no better equipped in their understanding of the relationship between autism and the MMR vaccine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most effective approach to vaccine hesitancy involves listening to concerns, acknowledging them respectfully, providing clear and accurate information, and making a strong recommendation for vaccination. In this case, directly addressing the autism concern with evidence-based information is most likely to lead to informed consent for vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Directly addressing the parent\u0027s specific concern is key to effective vaccine counselling.","Robust evidence shows no link between the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine and autism.","Building trust through clear communication is essential when addressing vaccine hesitancy."],"references":["https://www.chop.edu/centers-programs/vaccine-education-center/vaccines-and-other-conditions/vaccines-autism","https://talkingaboutimmunisation.org.au/What-about-autism","National Centre for Immunisaiton Research and Surveillance Australia - FAQ1- Quesitons about MMR/MMR Vaccine. Sept 2019. https://www.ncirs.org.au/mmrv-vaccine-decision-aid/faq1-questions-about-mmr-and-mmrv-vaccines","Why delayed vaccination schedules can be harmful to children. UNICEF. Available from: https://www.unicef.org/eca/stories/why-delayed-vaccination-schedules-can-be-harmful-children"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86537"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1527"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}}